title: For Sale:  Springfield M1903 Mark I Bolt Action Rifle 30-06
postcontent: World War I Springfield M1903 Mark I bolt action rifle in 30-06.  Stock and metal in good condition.  Bore is rough with pronounced rifling.  These Mark I's were modified to use the Pedersen Device toward the end of the first world war.  Cutout in the side of the reciever (see pic) facilitated the use of a 30 cal. pistol round to be fired.  Never really got into full service and most of the devices were destroyed with the few remaining in private collections and museums, as I understand it.  Stock is cartouched with both the serif P under the pistol grip and arsenal square along the side forward of the wrist. Initials inside the arsenal stamp are illegible.  Serial number in the 1,186,XXX range.  Barrel is marked U.S. with the bursting bomb and date of 5-09.  Purchased this rifle years ago from the grandson of old vet who stated it had been leaning against the wall inside a closet for more than 50 years.  I have fired it a few times and found it to function well with decent results at 100 yards.  Have a few more additional pics if you are serious.  Unable to get good pic of the bore.  Asking $850 .. will consider reasonable offer.  NO TRADES.  Located in Polk County, FL about 12 miles from Disney.

title: For Sale:  1941 Sako Finnish M39 w/ 1898 Tula receiver and straight stock
postcontent: Wow, if you looking to buy just one M39, this one is it.  But if you ben collecting M39s for a while you should know how rare of a find this one is.  When production begin on producing m39 at the Sako factory, Sako didn't have all the equipment in place to machine the pistol grip into the stock, so they produce the traditional straight grip stock that can be seen on earlier Finnish models.  A couple months later after about 6,200 straight grip stocks has been fitted to rifles, Sako acquired the correct equipment to machine the pistol grip.  Rifles with the straight grip stocks that returned to the factory during or after the war for repair or refurbishing, were fitted with the later pistol grip stock.  Truly a rare M39 with the straight stock.  The receiver on this rifle wasoriginal from the Tula factory which made this receiver in 1898.  This rifle is all matching in Finnish Style.  The condition of the rifle is very good, please keep in mind that the receiver is 118 years old.  The receiver is noticeable older looking when comparing it to the barrel and stock and does display some battle scars.  Barrel is in very good shape, good bluing and beautiful bore, with sharp rifling throughout.  Nice darker stain stock, with the correct proof marks, stock also show battle use, dings and scratches.   Email with phone number, or call or text me at REDACTED According to ATF ruling, due to the receiver being made in 1898, this firearm can ship directly to you without a ffl, consider an antique.  $45 to shipped insured.

title: For Sale/Trade:  AMT 25/22 Lightning
postcontent: The AMT 25/22 Lightning was made in Covina CA between 1984 and 1994.  It is an exact copy of the Ruger 10/22 but made from all stainless steel and has a factory overmolded Monte Carlo stock.  It weighs about 6.5 pounds, has a 22 inch crowned, plain tapered barrel without sights. AMT created the stainless steel 10/22 (as well as the first stainless steel MarkI pistol) copies of Ruger's guns before Ruger made them in stainless.  Ruger currently markets some of their 10/22's as stainless steel but, in fact, only the barrels are stainless.  The receivers and trigger groups are Aluminum Alloy.  AMT's guns (like this one) are ALL stainless steel.  AMT made two models - a folding stock tactical model and this harder to find Target model.

The new Walther SOFTCOIL™ gas-delayed blowback technology works to make the CCP an excellent concealed carry firearm. How Walther SOFTCOIL™ Technology Makes This Pistol A Must-Have  The CCP’s SOFTCOIL™ gas-delayed blowback system uses gas pressure from the ignited cartridge by directing it through a small port in the barrel in front of the chamber to slow down and delay the rearward motion of the slide. This is accomplished by means of a piston contained inside of a cylinder located under the barrel that opposes the rearward motion of the slide until the gas pressure has declined after the bullet has left the barrel. This allows the slide to end its rearward motion, opening the breech, and ejecting the empty cartridge case.
